  "prompt": "Who discovered Avogadro's number?",
  "response": "Amedeo Avogadro, an Italian scientist, first proposed the concept that equal volumes of gases at the same temperature and pressure contain the same number of molecules. This idea, known as **Avogadro's Law**, was introduced in 1811. However, Avogadro himself did not calculate the actual number of molecules in a mole, which is now known as **Avogadro's number**.\n\nThe determination of the value of Avogadro's number came much later, through the work of many scientists in the 19th and 20th centuries. Some key contributors include:\n\n1. **Jean Perrin (early 20th century)**: Through his work on Brownian motion and Einstein's theoretical predictions, Perrin was able to estimate Avogadro's number experimentally, earning him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1926.\n\n2. **Robert Millikan (early 20th century)**: His famous oil-drop experiment, which measured the charge of an electron, provided another method to estimate Avogadro's number.\n\nThe modern value of Avogadro's number, \\(6.02214076 \\times 10^{23}\\), was officially defined in 2019 as part of the redefinition of the mole in the International System of Units (SI). This fixed value is based on precise measurements and fundamental constants.",
